article.headline: Jackson State 71, Rutgers 70
article.story: PISCATAWAY, N.J. (AP) -- Catraiva Givens hit a 3-pointer from the right wing with :01 to play to give Jackson State a 71-70 victory over Rutgers on Tuesday night. Trey Johnson, who was averaging 32 points, scored 20 points and made a 30-foot pass from the backcourt to Givens for the game-winning shot that gave Jackson State its first win in five games, including three against Top 25 teams. Kay Martinez added 17 points for the Tigers, who blew a 15-point second-half lead before rallying in the final seconds. Givens made all three of his shots and finished with eight points. Courtney Nelson had given Rutgers (1-2) a 70-68 lead with a 3-pointer from the left wing with 1:11 to play. Marquis Webb then stole a Julius Young pass with 32 seconds to play and the Scarlet Knights seemed to be in control. However, Webb was called for a five-second violation with 19 seconds to go, giving Jackson State a final chance. After the ball was knocked out of bounds with 8.2 seconds left, Johnson ran to the backcourt to take an inbound pass near the Rutgers foul line. Seeing he was double-teamed, he fired the pass to Givens. Webb and J.R. Inman had 12 points apiece for Rutgers, while Adrian Hill, Hamady N'Diaye and Jaron Griffin had 11 points apiece. There were four lead changes and one tie in the final six minutes. Layups by Griffin and Webb gave Rutgers a 62-59 lead before Johnson tied the game at 62 with three straight free throws. A dunk by Hill put Rutgers ahead 64-62, but Young hit a 3-pointer and a layup to give the Tigers a 67-64 lead. The margin was still three points when Anthony Farmer hit a floater with 1:40 to go and then Nelson drained his 3-pointer after Johnson was called for an offensive foul. Martinez came off the bench in the first half and scored 13 points in a 20-6 run that gave Jackson State of the Southwestern Athletic Conference a 35-25 lead. The Tigers led 40-31 at the half and pushed their margin to 47-32 early in the second half on a layup by Darrion Griffin. Rutgers didn't get going until Webb and Inman hit 3-pointers to ignite a 17-5 spurt that got the Scarlet Knights within 56-55 on two free throws by Jaron Griffin with 8:29 to play. Jackson State opened the season with road games against Alabama, Georgia Tech, Illinois and Memphis.
